lVe have in this chapter three chain arguments to prove that the wise man cannot suffer annoyance, the first occupy- ing the whole of ἓ 143 the second from praeterea down to non cadet zg’z'tur in sap. aegritudOE the third from et quem ad modum to the end of ξ 15. The stages in the first argument are the following: he who is brave is also confident: he who is confident does not sear: but he who is liable to annoyance is also liable to sear: hence liability to annoyance is out of keeping with bravery. At this point Cicero takes a new start and brings the argument down to the same point by another set of inferences, viz.—he who is liable to annoyance would seem liable to sear, loss of spirit, despondency: he who is liable to these is liable to become a slave, to admit defeat: he who is liable to this is liable to timidity and cowardice:
